		<li>☐ Contractor license information (if using contractor)</li>
		<li>☐ Proof of property ownership or authorization</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Permit Costs and Fees (2024)</h2>

	<h3>Standard Permit Fees</h3>
	<p>Stockton fence permit fees are based on project valuation:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Base permit fee:</strong> $150-300 for typical residential fence</li>
		<li><strong>Plan check fee:</strong> 65% of permit fee</li>
		<li><strong>Technology fee:</strong> Additional $15-25</li>
		<li><strong>Total typical cost:</strong> $250-500 for average project</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Additional Potential Fees</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Variance application:</strong> $500-1,000 if you need exceptions</li>
		<li><strong>Revision fees:</strong> $100-200 for plan modifications</li>
		<li><strong>Inspection fees:</strong> Usually included in permit, but re-inspections may cost extra</li>
		<li><strong>Late fees:</strong> Working without permit can result in double permit fees</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Fee Waivers and Reductions</h3>
	<p>Some situations may qualify for reduced fees:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Emergency repairs:</strong> Storm damage requiring immediate fence repair</li>
		<li><strong>Code compliance:</strong> Bringing existing non-compliant fence up to code</li>
		<li><strong>Senior citizen discount:</strong> May be available for homeowner-occupied residences</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>HOA Requirements and Approvals</h2>

	<h3>Understanding HOA Authority</h3>
	<p>If your property is in an HOA community, you must obtain HOA approval BEFORE applying for a city permit:</p>

	<h4>Common HOA Restrictions:</h4>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Material requirements:</strong> May require specific fence types (wood, vinyl, etc.)</li>
		<li><strong>Color restrictions:</strong> Often limited to approved color palette</li>
		<li><strong>Style requirements:</strong> Decorative elements, panel orientation</li>
		<li><strong>Height limits:</strong> May be more restrictive than city code</li>
		<li><strong>Front yard prohibitions:</strong> Some HOAs ban front yard fencing entirely</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>HOA Approval Process</h3>
	<p>Typical steps for HOA approval:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Review CC&Rs:</strong> Check your community's governing documents</li>
		<li><strong>Submit application:</strong> HOA architectural review request</li>
		<li><strong>Include plans:</strong> Detailed drawings and material specifications</li>
		<li><strong>Wait for review:</strong> Can take 30-60 days depending on HOA</li>
		<li><strong>Attend meeting:</strong> May need to present at board meeting</li>
		<li><strong>Get written approval:</strong> Required for city permit application</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>What If HOA Denies Your Request?</h3>
	<p>You have options if your fence plan is rejected:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Revise plans:</strong> Modify design to meet HOA requirements</li>
		<li><strong>Appeal decision:</strong> Most HOAs have an appeal process</li>
		<li><strong>Request variance:</strong> Explain special circumstances</li>
		<li><strong>Mediation:</strong> Some disputes can be mediated</li>
		<li><strong>Legal action:</strong> Last resort for unreasonable denials</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Property Line and Setback Requirements</h2>

	<h3>Understanding Property Lines</h3>
	<p>Building exactly on property lines requires careful consideration:</p>

	<h4>Fences ON the Property Line:</h4>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Shared ownership:</strong> You and neighbor own fence equally</li>
		<li><strong>Shared cost:</strong> Both parties typically split installation and maintenance</li>
		<li><strong>Shared decisions:</strong> Both must agree to changes or removal</li>
		<li><strong>Liability:</strong> Both parties responsible for fence condition</li>
		<li><strong>Written agreement recommended:</strong> Document cost sharing and maintenance</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Fences Inside Your Property:</h4>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Full ownership:</strong> You own and maintain fence alone</li>
		<li><strong>Setback distance:</strong> Typically 6-12 inches from property line</li>
		<li><strong>Access easement:</strong> Allows you to maintain both sides</li>
		<li><strong>Fewer disputes:</strong> Neighbor doesn't own or have rights to fence</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Survey Requirements</h3>
	<p>Knowing exact property lines prevents legal problems:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Professional survey:</strong> Most accurate method ($400-800 in Stockton)</li>
		<li><strong>Property pins:</strong> Locate existing survey markers</li>
		<li><strong>Title report:</strong> Shows recorded boundaries and easements</li>
		<li><strong>Fence in wrong place:</strong> Can be forced to move or remove entirely</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Inspection Requirements</h2>

	<h3>Required Inspections</h3>
	<p>Stockton typically requires these fence inspections:</p>

	<h4>Post-Hole Inspection (Before Concrete):</h4>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>When to call:</strong> After holes dug but before setting posts</li>
		<li><strong>Inspector checks:</strong> Depth, diameter, alignment</li>
		<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> Typically 1/3 of post length, minimum 24" deep</li>
		<li><strong>Don't:</strong> Fill holes before inspection or risk failing</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Final Inspection:</h4>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>When to call:</strong> After fence completely installed</li>
		<li><strong>Inspector checks:</strong> Height, setbacks, structural integrity, materials</li>
		<li><strong>Requirements:</strong> Matches approved plans, meets code</li>
		<li><strong>Passing:</strong> Receives approval and permit can be closed</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Scheduling Inspections</h3>
	<p>How to request inspections:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Phone:</strong> Call (209) 937-8561 at least 24 hours in advance</li>
		<li><strong>Online:</strong> Schedule through ePermitting portal</li>
		<li><strong>Time windows:</strong> Usually AM (8-12) or PM (1-4) slots</li>
		<li><strong>Be present:</strong> Or have contractor available to answer questions</li>
		<li><strong>Corrections:</strong> If failed, make required changes and re-schedule</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Common Permit Violations and Penalties</h2>

	<h3>Violations That Trigger Enforcement</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>No permit:</strong> Building without required permits</li>
		<li><strong>Exceeding height:</strong> Fence taller than allowed</li>
		<li><strong>Blocking visibility:</strong> Creating traffic hazards at corners</li>
		<li><strong>Wrong materials:</strong> Using prohibited materials (barbed wire in residential)</li>
		<li><strong>Encroachment:</strong> Building over property line onto neighbor's land</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Enforcement Actions</h3>
	<p>What happens when violations are discovered:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Notice of violation:</strong> Written notification of code violation</li>
		<li><strong>Correction period:</strong> Typically 30-90 days to fix or obtain permits</li>
		<li><strong>Fines:</strong> $100-500 per day for continuing violations</li>
		<li><strong>Stop work order:</strong> Must halt construction immediately</li>
		<li><strong>Forced removal:</strong> City can require fence removal at your expense</li>
		<li><strong>Title issues:</strong> Violations can complicate selling property</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Reporting Violations</h3>
	<p>Anyone can report suspected code violations:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Neighbors:</strong> Most common source of complaints</li>
		<li><strong>City inspectors:</strong> Routine patrols and satellite monitoring</li>
		<li><strong>Title companies:</strong> During real estate transactions</li>
		<li><strong>Anonymous reports:</strong> Can be made without identifying reporter</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Special Circumstances and Variances</h2>

	<h3>When You Need a Variance</h3>
	<p>Situations that may require variance approval:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Height exception:</strong> Need fence taller than code allows</li>
		<li><strong>Front yard placement:</strong> Special security or privacy needs</li>
		<li><strong>Unusual property:</strong> Irregular lots with unique challenges</li>
		<li><strong>Historic district:</strong> Properties in historic preservation areas</li>
		<li><strong>Topography issues:</strong> Slopes or elevation changes</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Variance Application Process</h3>
	<p>How to request exceptions to standard rules:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Application fee:</strong> $500-1,000 for variance request</li>
		<li><strong>Justification:</strong> Must show hardship or special circumstances</li>
		<li><strong>Neighbor notification:</strong> Properties within 300 feet notified</li>
		<li><strong>Public hearing:</strong> Planning Commission reviews request</li>
		<li><strong>Decision timeline:</strong> Can take 60-90 days</li>
		<li><strong>Appeal rights:</strong> Neighbors can appeal approval</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Pool Fence Special Requirements</h2>

	<h3>California Pool Barrier Law</h3>
	<p>Pool fences must meet strict safety standards:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Minimum height:</strong> 60 inches (5 feet)</li>
		<li><strong>No gaps:</strong> Spacing no more than 4 inches</li>
		<li><strong>Self-closing gates:</strong> Must close and latch automatically</li>
		<li><strong>Latch height:</strong> Minimum 54 inches from ground</li>
		<li><strong>No climbing aids:</strong> Nothing within 45 inches that could help children climb</li>
		<li><strong>Gate swing:</strong> Must swing away from pool</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Additional Pool Fence Considerations</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Permit always required:</strong> No exceptions for pool enclosures</li>
		<li><strong>Strict inspections:</strong> Safety compliance carefully checked</li>
		<li><strong>House as barrier:</strong> If house serves as one side, windows/doors must have alarms</li>
		<li><strong>Removable fencing:</strong> Must meet same standards as permanent</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Working with Contractors</h2>

	<h3>Contractor Responsibilities</h3>
	<p>Licensed contractors should handle permit process:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Permit pulling:</strong> Contractor typically obtains permits</li>
		<li><strong>Plan preparation:</strong> Creates required drawings and specifications</li>
		<li><strong>Code knowledge:</strong> Ensures compliance with all regulations</li>
		<li><strong>Inspection scheduling:</strong> Arranges and attends inspections</li>
		<li><strong>Corrections:</strong> Fixes any issues found during inspection</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Verify Contractor Credentials</h3>
	<p>Protect yourself by checking contractor qualifications:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>License verification:</strong> Check at cslb.ca.gov</li>
		<li><strong>Active license:</strong> Must be current and in good standing</li>
		<li><strong>Insurance:</strong> Verify liability and workers comp coverage</li>
		<li><strong>Bond:</strong> California contractors must be bonded</li>
		<li><strong>Local knowledge:</strong> Familiar with Stockton requirements</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Timeline Expectations</h2>

	<h3>Typical Project Timeline</h3>
	<p>Plan for these timeframes when scheduling your fence:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>HOA approval (if required):</strong> 30-60 days</li>
		<li><strong>Permit application:</strong> 1-2 days to prepare and submit</li>
		<li><strong>City review:</strong> 5-10 business days</li>
		<li><strong>Corrections (if needed):</strong> 3-7 days to revise and resubmit</li>
		<li><strong>Permit issuance:</strong> 1-2 days after approval</li>
		<li><strong>Installation:</strong> 1-5 days depending on fence size</li>
		<li><strong>Final inspection:</strong> Schedule at completion</li>
		<li><strong>Total timeline:</strong> 6-12 weeks from start to finish</li>
	</ul>

